ncounters with Protestant and Catholic Christianity, Judaism, Islam, and Hinduism. While acknowledging the necessity of the Enlightenment emphasis on toleration and peaceful religious coexistence, these scholars nevertheless have grave misgivings about the Enlightenment's spiritually thin secularism. The authors ultimately upend both the claim that the West's experience offers a ready-made template for the world to follow and the belief that the West's achievements are to be ignored, despised, or discarded.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnlightenment. 0aIslam. 0aReligion and politics. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aElshtain, Jean Bethke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalston, William A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHashmi, Sohail H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMehta, Pratap Bhanu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovak, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwen IV, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOwen, J. Judd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwen, J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOwen, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPangle, Thomas L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapini, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSachedina, Abdulaziz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWitte, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97